  <li id="comment-39281" class="comment even thread-even depth-1">
    <header class="comment--meta">
      <div class="vcard"><cite class="comment-author fn"><a href="https://www.blogger.com/profile/02174295191363694422" class="url" rel="ugc external nofollow">Navigating the Mothership</a></cite></div>
      <a href="https://orangette.net/2013/01/ah-ha/#comment-39281"><time class="comment-time" datetime="2013-01-06T03:13:13-05:00">Sunday, January 6, 2013 at 3:13 am</time></a>    </header>

    
    <div class="comment--content">
      <p>What a beauty!</p>
<p>And I, too, found myself dealing with PPD in addition to PPA after the birth of my second child. Part of it related to some minor but crappy life circumstances but a lot of it was exhaustion. I imagine if I had gotten more sleep in my pregnancy &#038; in the first 6 months of my boy&#39;s life I would not have slumped as low as I did. And the other thing that was tricky for me in terms of recognizing PPD was that I never felt SO low. But certainly miserable, and I knew that I shouldn&#39;t be feeling miserable in my &#8220;happy&#8221; life. Anyway, I wrote a post about it if you are interested: <a href="http://navigatingthemothership.blogspot.com/2012/05/all-i-can-do-is-keep-breathing.html" rel="nofollow ugc">http://navigatingthemothership.blogspot.com/2012/05/all-i-can-do-is-keep-breathing.html</a></p>
<p>I think sharing is good and helpful to so many others. </p>
<p>Hope you are feeling more joy and ease in your life very soon!</p>
    </div>

