      <div class="vcard"><cite class="comment-author fn"><a href="https://www.blogger.com/profile/15777890127125999435" class="url" rel="ugc external nofollow">Fran</a></cite></div>
      <a href="https://orangette.net/2013/01/ah-ha/#comment-39294"><time class="comment-time" datetime="2013-01-06T04:50:22-05:00">Sunday, January 6, 2013 at 4:50 am</time></a>    </header>

    
    <div class="comment--content">
      <p>I love that you had the courage to post this! I had my first baby about a month after June was born (I was rather envious when I read your post announcing her birth ;-)). While I haven&#39;t experienced depression I have found that many of the books meant to help romanticize the entire experience from pregnancy to delivery to nursing to learning to care for this person in a way that is unhelpful, unrealistic, and can easily make a &#8220;normal&#8221; person think they have a problem for having struggles or not enjoying every bit of it. So thanks for sharing when things aren&#39;t perfect, I&#39;ll be praying for you and Brandon and June. </p>
    </div>

      </li><!-- #comment-## -->
