  <li id="comment-39466" class="comment even thread-even depth-1">
    <header class="comment--meta">
      <div class="vcard"><cite class="comment-author fn">Anonymous</cite></div>
      <a href="https://orangette.net/2013/01/ah-ha/#comment-39466"><time class="comment-time" datetime="2013-01-08T22:47:37-05:00">Tuesday, January 8, 2013 at 10:47 pm</time></a>    </header>

    
    <div class="comment--content">
      <p>Hi Molly, </p>
<p>I&#39;m a sister-in-arms. I&#39;ve experienced post-partum depression twice. </p>
<p>There are many different ways to get help and help yourself and all of them are good. What was most beneficial to me was the philosophy of self-help of the Pacific Postpartum Support Society (up the road from you here, in Vancouver BC). I began to engineer a plan for myself to recover, and that sense of agency was the most important step. My personal plan started with maximizing my sleep, by any means necessary. I also addressed nutrition, including supplementing with vitamin D and omega-3s. I also made sure to get time to exercise a little bit. I saw a cognitive behavioural counsellor. The second time around I attended a support group for women with postpartum depression. I was initially afraid of sharing my feelings in an environment like that, but it actually became a huge bright point to organize my week around. Thinking a lot about motherhood also helped (I&#39;m more of an intellectual and less of an intuitive) &#8212; especially thinking of it as a marathon for which I had no training. It was bound to be very very difficult at first, but as I went on, with the right supports in place, I would adapt and become more adept. For some of my fellow support group attendees, weaning, anti-depressants or anti-anxiety medications, vacations, yoga, massage, etc. were very helpful.</p>
<p>The most important strategy for dealing with postpartum depression, for me &#8212; and this is what the group facilitator emphasized for all of us &#8212; was to make a self-care plan each week. What did I need: company? a food treat? time to read, all alone? yoga? A shower? A pedicure? A walk by the oceans? And then the task is to get these things.</p>
<p>The other most important thing to know is that this IS temporary. It feels like it goes on forever and forever and forever, but it will not last forever. You will have some better days, and then those better days will become good days, and then those good days will outnumber the bad ones. You may find that all of a sudden you&#39;re feeling worse than before, but it&#39;ll just be a dip on the road to recovering yourself. </p>
<p>You&#39;ve probably already found this: <a href="http://www.ppmdsupport.com/" rel="nofollow ugc">http://www.ppmdsupport.com/</a> and if you&#39;re able to read more, I highly recommend PostPartum Depression for Dummies. (available as an ebook through Seattle Public Library <a href="http://seattle.bibliocommons.com/item/show/2440602030_postpartum_depression_for_dummies" rel="nofollow ugc">http://seattle.bibliocommons.com/item/show/2440602030_postpartum_depression_for_dummies</a>) </p>
<p>My heart is with you. You&#39;re the best mother for your baby and you are all going to be okay. </p>
<p>With love,</p>
<p>Heather </p>
    </div>

      </li><!-- #comment-## -->
