    <div class="comment--content">
      <p>I will add my voice to the masses in thanking you for sharing this post and your situation. Like many others who have posted here so far, I too suffered from PPD, and like you I never recognized it because it didn&#39;t feel like &#8220;depression&#8221;. I felt anxious, overwhelmed, manic, angry and desperate in varying amounts from day to day and moment to moment. I remember clearly wondering at one particularly dark moment if I could just get in my car and drive away from my beautiful but sleepless baby and inhumanly patient husband. Luckily I didn&#39;t and those feelings did eventually pass. Looking back I can now see that I was indeed suffering from both the massive personal upheaval that new motherhood brings and the hormonal onslaught of PPD. My son is now a healthy, happy and secure almost three year old, and aside from occasional moments of frustration with his (totally normal and thankfully rare) whining or tantrums, I feel completely in control of my emotions again. You too will get through this, as so many of us have. Because as all of the cliches rightly tell us, admitting you have a problem is the first step and reaching out is the second. I thank you for your bravery and candor, and hope that your story inspires more completely normal women and wonderful mothers (who also happen to have PPD) to do the same.</p>
