  <li id="comment-39519" class="comment even thread-even depth-1">
    <header class="comment--meta">
      <div class="vcard"><cite class="comment-author fn"><a href="https://www.blogger.com/profile/05096845872314411400" class="url" rel="ugc external nofollow">knitme23</a></cite></div>
      <a href="https://orangette.net/2013/01/ah-ha/#comment-39519"><time class="comment-time" datetime="2013-01-12T16:43:43-05:00">Saturday, January 12, 2013 at 4:43 pm</time></a>    </header>

    
    <div class="comment--content">
      <p>I know you&#39;re getting the affirmation and support you need from all these comments (and all that love!), but I wanted to add my belated voice, too. I had a mild case of ppd with my first (wonderful, easy) and then a stronger case with my second (also wonderful, easy) son: and the voice in my head kept slapping me around for being *such a wimp!* and *such a bad mom!* for feeling so wiped out and crying so easily and feeling like I&#39;d never, ever, ever get my/a &#8220;real life&#8221; back. . .  Luckily it just passed in about a month, but that experience helped me recognize a later bout of just plain regular depression. . .  and taught me that wow. It&#39;s tough to shake and truly weird and debilitating. Hope you are loving yourself and continuing to reach out and take. care! I love reading Anne Lamott&#39;s Traveling Mercies when I&#39;m struggling, and her idea of small steps through the dark has been very helpful to me. Warm thoughts and best wishes. </p>
    </div>

      </li><!-- #comment-## -->
  <li id="comment-39935" class="comment odd alt thread-odd thread-alt depth-1">
    <header class="comment--meta">
      <div class="vcard"><cite class="comment-author fn"><a href="https://www.blogger.com/profile/05096845872314411400" class="url" rel="ugc external nofollow">knitme23</a></cite></div>
      <a href="https://orangette.net/2013/01/ah-ha/#comment-39935"><time class="comment-time" datetime="2013-01-12T16:43:43-05:00">Saturday, January 12, 2013 at 4:43 pm</time></a>    </header>

    
    <div class="comment--content">
      <p>I know you&#39;re getting the affirmation and support you need from all these comments (and all that love!), but I wanted to add my belated voice, too. I had a mild case of ppd with my first (wonderful, easy) and then a stronger case with my second (also wonderful, easy) son: and the voice in my head kept slapping me around for being *such a wimp!* and *such a bad mom!* for feeling so wiped out and crying so easily and feeling like I&#39;d never, ever, ever get my/a &#8220;real life&#8221; back. . .  Luckily it just passed in about a month, but that experience helped me recognize a later bout of just plain regular depression. . .  and taught me that wow. It&#39;s tough to shake and truly weird and debilitating. Hope you are loving yourself and continuing to reach out and take. care! I love reading Anne Lamott&#39;s Traveling Mercies when I&#39;m struggling, and her idea of small steps through the dark has been very helpful to me. Warm thoughts and best wishes. </p>
    </div>

      </li><!-- #comment-## -->
