  <li id="comment-39549" class="comment even thread-even depth-1">
    <header class="comment--meta">
      <div class="vcard"><cite class="comment-author fn">sarah</cite></div>
      <a href="https://orangette.net/2013/01/ah-ha/#comment-39549"><time class="comment-time" datetime="2013-01-16T22:54:41-05:00">Wednesday, January 16, 2013 at 10:54 pm</time></a>    </header>

    
    <div class="comment--content">
      <p>Thank you for writing this. My baby was born 6 months ago and at first, despite him being in intensive care, I felt fine. But slowly this feeling of wrongness just kept building and worsening. I didn&#39;t think it was PPD because I didn&#39;t feel sad exactly, just wrong, not me, sort of isolated. It was like I was insulated from the world and angry at the same time if that makes any sense. Angry with the world, my partner, everyone except the baby (thank God). I&#39;d look at his perfect little face and think why am I not happier? I never told anyone because I was terrified they would find out what an awful mother I clearly was and I somehow managed to fake it through meeting friends etc. Reading this and the comments made me think for the first time that maybe this was hormonal not just me being an unfit mother. It gave me the confidence to speak to my doctor about getting help but (and this is why I am writing this) then 2 days ago my period suddenly started even though I&#39;m still breastfeeding and honestly, it is like a cloud has lifted. So thank you for having the courage to write this, I hope other women who are where I was 3 months ago see your post and don&#39;t have to go through all this agony. And also thanks to the kind person who mentioned the Cup of Jo article that made my sudden lift make sense. I hope your reprieve is in sight too, you are in my thoughts. </p>
    </div>

      </li><!-- #comment-## -->
