  <li id="comment-39596" class="comment even thread-even depth-1">
    <header class="comment--meta">
      <div class="vcard"><cite class="comment-author fn"><a href="https://www.blogger.com/profile/07651169336611127729" class="url" rel="ugc external nofollow">coffeegirlkristen</a></cite></div>
      <a href="https://orangette.net/2013/01/ah-ha/#comment-39596"><time class="comment-time" datetime="2013-02-08T18:16:39-05:00">Friday, February 8, 2013 at 6:16 pm</time></a>    </header>

    
    <div class="comment--content">
      <p>Oh Molly. The place you are in resonates. I had ppd after my second daughter was born, 18 months after her sister. My husband worked two jobs &#038; classes. I was 22, hours from family and felt completely overwhelmed and even worse- hopeless. My sisters had never felt that way and tried to tell me I was fine which just made me feel crazy. I remember reading somewhere &#8220;how do you eat a whale?&#8221; and thinking &#39;you can&#39;t, that&#39;s ridiculous&#39; and seeing the answer &#8220;one bite at a time&#8221;. I suddenly realized that it was the big picture (the whale) that was freaking me out. I stopped worrying about the whale, and just worried about the bite in front of me. I also learned about what I call &#8220;survival mode&#8221;. This week I used survival mode while I was sick &#038; hubby was on duty (we have 4 kids now!). Survival mode is this. I must breathe, I must make sure kids eat. The rest is gravy. Maybe they don&#39;t get veg that day, maybe they wear dirty socks tomorrow. WE WILL SURVIVE! And mankind has &#038; does survive much worse. Read Little House books to little June someday. Thinking of those pioneer moms dealing with blizzards and no running water helped me put &#8220;survival mode&#8221; into historical perspective. </p>
    </div>

      </li><!-- #comment-## -->
  <li id="comment-40012" class="comment odd alt thread-odd thread-alt depth-1">
    <header class="comment--meta">
      <div class="vcard"><cite class="comment-author fn"><a href="https://www.blogger.com/profile/07651169336611127729" class="url" rel="ugc external nofollow">coffeegirlkristen</a></cite></div>
      <a href="https://orangette.net/2013/01/ah-ha/#comment-40012"><time class="comment-time" datetime="2013-02-08T18:16:39-05:00">Friday, February 8, 2013 at 6:16 pm</time></a>    </header>

    
    <div class="comment--content">
      <p>Oh Molly. The place you are in resonates. I had ppd after my second daughter was born, 18 months after her sister. My husband worked two jobs &#038; classes. I was 22, hours from family and felt completely overwhelmed and even worse- hopeless. My sisters had never felt that way and tried to tell me I was fine which just made me feel crazy. I remember reading somewhere &#8220;how do you eat a whale?&#8221; and thinking &#39;you can&#39;t, that&#39;s ridiculous&#39; and seeing the answer &#8220;one bite at a time&#8221;. I suddenly realized that it was the big picture (the whale) that was freaking me out. I stopped worrying about the whale, and just worried about the bite in front of me. I also learned about what I call &#8220;survival mode&#8221;. This week I used survival mode while I was sick &#038; hubby was on duty (we have 4 kids now!). Survival mode is this. I must breathe, I must make sure kids eat. The rest is gravy. Maybe they don&#39;t get veg that day, maybe they wear dirty socks tomorrow. WE WILL SURVIVE! And mankind has &#038; does survive much worse. Read Little House books to little June someday. Thinking of those pioneer moms dealing with blizzards and no running water helped me put &#8220;survival mode&#8221; into historical perspective. </p>
    </div>

      </li><!-- #comment-## -->
  <li id="comment-39597" class="comment even thread-even depth-1">
    <header class="comment--meta">
      <div class="vcard"><cite class="comment-author fn"><a href="https://www.blogger.com/profile/07651169336611127729" class="url" rel="ugc external nofollow">coffeegirlkristen</a></cite></div>
      <a href="https://orangette.net/2013/01/ah-ha/#comment-39597"><time class="comment-time" datetime="2013-02-08T18:33:46-05:00">Friday, February 8, 2013 at 6:33 pm</time></a>    </header>

    
    <div class="comment--content">
      <p>This mom brain! I swear! The thing I intended to say before I got into that long memory, was this: FlyLady.net. I heard about her on a mom website and she saved my life. She is all about baby steps, and how to keep up when your aren&#39;t a born organized type of gal. She does what she does for free and thousands of moms have been able to get their heads above water thanks to her. Just ask around!</p>
    </div>

      </li><!-- #comment-## -->
